	<!---about -->
	<section id="about-page"class="screen-container">
		<div id="gray2"></div>

		<div id="about-text">

			<h1 >ABOUT</h1>
			<p><span class="M">M</span>y website introduces abstract English letterforms, that are made of CSS code and shows an interaction between English and Korean letters. The interaction is based on a system called Romanization of Korean. — it refers to writing Korean words using the Latin script : either romanizing individual words in a Korean text or writing an entire Korean text in the Latin script.
			</p>

			<p>
				<span class="ttt"></span>To make the connection, when you hover the Black English letter form, it transforms into White Korean letterform, which is either a singular Korean consonant or vowel, that has a similar sound as the English letterform.: A, B, D, E, G, H, I, J, K, L, M, N, O, P, S, T, U.
  If a letter returns back as black, it means it doesn't have any sound match with one single Korean character.: C, F, Q, R, V, W, X, Y, Z.
 To be specific, when writing a letter 'C' sound in Korean, it needs to combine more than one Korean consonant and vowel. In other words, there is no single Korean character that sounds match with letter C
			</p>
		</div>

	</section>

	<section id="nemo-page" class="screen-container overflowHidden">
		<div id="gray3">

		</div>
		<div id="nemo-text">
			<h1 class="C2">NEMO </h1>
			<p class""numnum>Letter forms on the left side represent numbers, 0 to 9 in order. <br>The rest two are Exclamation mark and question mark.  </p>
			<p >
<span class="M">M<span class="M">y font name is Nemo, which means square in Korean. The letterforms are all fit into the same size square, which proposition is 8:9. So all the width and the height of the letterforms are the same. I was inspired by Bauhaus font so they look pretty abstract and feels heavy. Also, elements of letterforms are composed of basic shapes: square, circle, and triangle.
</p>
		</div>
